On March 2, 2018, President Donald Trump issued an executive order to continue the national emergency declared in Executive Order 13692, which was issued on March 8, 2015. The national emergency was declared in response to the erosion of human rights guarantees, persecution of political opponents, curtailment of press freedoms, violence and human rights violations in Venezuela. The executive order also referenced the establishment of an illegitimate Constituent Assembly, public corruption, and repression and persecution of the political opposition. The President stated that these circumstances continue to pose an unusual and extraordinary threat to the national security and foreign policy of the United States. The continuation of the national emergency was done in accordance with the National Emergencies Act.